Write test fixtures and tests for the file encoding and line termination.

Prepare 6 files containing this lisp expression:
------------------------------------------------------------------------
(setq
 text
 (strcat
   "« À Noël, l'âgé Ægyr brûla du maïs rôti près d'un cañon où Foedor "
   "jugea déçu que l'île exiguë, bâtie sur du würmien, était trop naïve "
   "pour Zoë et Cécÿle. »"))
------------------------------------------------------------------------

encoded in utf-8 and in iso-8859-1
and with dos, mac and unix line terminations.

1- Write a script using alfe to load them using -e {utf-8,iso-8859-1,us-ascii}x{-mac,-dos,-unix,}

- expect read errors when the wrong encoding or line-termination is used.

- check that the text variable is equal to:
   "« À Noël, l'âgé Ægyr brûla du maïs rôti près d'un cañon où Foedor jugea déçu que l'île exiguë, bâtie sur du würmien, était trop naïve pour Zoë et Cécÿle. »"
  (be careful with the encoding when doing the check, and reset the text variable before loading each file).

2- Write a script using alfe to read the files with read-line using  -e {utf-8,iso-8859-1,us-ascii}x{-mac,-dos,-unix,}

with the same expectations for errors,
and verifying the content of the file is read correctly.


2- Write an autolisp program, that loops on the *AUTOLISP-FILE-ENCODING*
  variables to try to load and to read (read-line) each file with the various
  encoding-line-terminations combination and perform the same
  expectations and checks as in the script. 
  
Note: since *AUTOLISP-FILE-ENCODING* is writable, we can change it
between two calls to load or open (and then read, read-line, and read-char).

Note: AFAIK in autocad and bricscad, you can only choose the encoding
at load or open time, not for each read, read-line or read-char
call. This should be verified (documentation and tests of the *cad),
and the autolisp-spec should be updated to precise this fact. The
clautolisp extension using *AUTOLISP-FILE-ENCODING* as defaut encoding
for load and open should be precised, and the fact that the encoding
doesn't change between read, read-line, read-char calls (or
print/write calls).

== Status (2026-06-23) ==

Fixture sentence corrected to be ISO-8859-1-safe (pbourguignon): U+0153
(oe ligature) is ISO-8859-15, not ISO-8859-1, so it is written "oe"
(Foedor); U+2019 (right single quote) is written "'". The sentence now
contains only code points <= U+00FF, so it encodes in BOTH UTF-8 and
ISO-8859-1.

DONE — the 6-fixture encoding x line-termination matrix, as file-compat
round-trip scenarios:

  clautolisp/autolisp-file-compat/scenarios/encodings/french-{utf8,latin1}-{unix,dos,mac}.sexp
  (+ byte-exact reference artifacts under .../artifacts/)

Each writes the sentence with its :external-format (:utf-8 / :iso-8859-1)
and :newline-mode (:lf / :crlf / :cr), reads it back, and asserts the
decoded text/lines round-trip. All 6 pass (verified bytes: UTF-8 «=c2 ab,
À=c3 80; ISO-8859-1 «=ab, À=c0; newline lf=0a, crlf=0d 0a, cr=0d). This
covers the codec + line-termination half of parts 1-2. (Non-LF variants
assert via :expected-lines, since the raw read-back retains the CR/CRLF
terminator — same convention as the existing crlf-text / cr-only-text
scenarios.)

FINDING — RESOLVED 1.2.12 (open-write-ignores-file-encoding.issue, now
in issues/closed/). (open PATH "w") + princ/write-line now honours
*AUTOLISP-FILE-ENCODING* / -e for the write encoding (default lookup
added in OPEN-DEFAULT-EXTERNAL-FORMAT, mirroring the read path). So the
engine no longer blocks a pure-AutoLISP program from authoring its own
UTF-8 fixtures. Parts 1 & 3 are unblocked at the engine level; what
remains for them is CAD-parity confirmation of the chosen write
encoding + the spec update (see REMAINING). Original finding kept below
for context.

FINDING (originally blocked parts 1 & 3 as written) — AutoLISP write
ignored the requested encoding:

  At the AutoLISP level, `(open PATH "w")` followed by `princ`/`write-line`
  writes ISO-8859-1 / ANSI bytes REGARDLESS of *AUTOLISP-FILE-ENCODING*
  or the CLI `-e` flag. Verified: writing "é" yields the single byte E9
  under both `*AUTOLISP-FILE-ENCODING* "utf-8"` and `... "iso-8859-1"`,
  and likewise under `-e utf-8` / `-e iso-8859-1`. READ does honor the
  requested encoding (a UTF-8 `load` of those Latin-1 bytes signals a
  UTF-8 stream-decoding error). So:
    - read/load/read-line  -> honor *AUTOLISP-FILE-ENCODING* / -e  (good)
    - open-for-write/princ -> always Latin-1/ANSI                 (bug?)
  This is why parts 1 & 3 cannot yet be realized as a pure-AutoLISP
  program that AUTHORS its own UTF-8 fixtures and loads them back: the
  authoring step can't produce UTF-8 from AutoLISP. The file-compat
  scenarios above sidestep it by writing the artifacts at the CL level.

  Whether open-for-write SHOULD honor *AUTOLISP-FILE-ENCODING* is a
  CAD-parity question (what byte sequence do AutoCAD / BricsCAD write for
  a non-ASCII char under a chosen code page?) — exactly the kind of thing
  this issue says must be verified against the *cads and then specified.

REMAINING (needs CAD access / spec authority):
  - decide + fix the open-for-write encoding behaviour (above), then add
    the part-1 (LOAD a `(setq text (strcat …))` fixture per encoding) and
    part-3 (loop over *AUTOLISP-FILE-ENCODING*) AutoLISP test programs,
    including the wrong-encoding / wrong-line-termination error cases;
  - verify the per-open (not per-read) encoding-selection against AutoCAD
    and BricsCAD and update the autolisp-spec accordingly.
